SIMPLE: clatch
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Clatch
<hw>Clatch</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Scot.
<ets>clatch</ets> a slap, the noise caused by the collision of soft
bodies; prob. of imitative origin.]</ety> <fld>(Scot. & Dial.
Eng.)</fld> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A soft or sloppy lump or mass; <as>as, to
throw a <ex>clatch</ex> of mud</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Anything put together or made in a careless or
slipshod way; hence, a sluttish or slipshod woman.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Clatch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Clatch
<hw>Clatch</hw>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <def>To daub or smear, as with
lime; to make or finish in a slipshod way.</def>
<mark>[Scot.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Clathraceae</ent>⟦br⟧
